<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "How much compost do I need for a garden bed?", answer: "For an established garden bed, apply 1 to 2 inches of compost and work it into the top 6 inches of soil. For a 100 square foot bed at 2 inches of compost, that is 16.7 cubic feet, which is 0.62 cubic yards or 17 bags of the standard 1 cubic foot bag. New beds or very depleted soils can handle 3 to 4 inches of compost at once." },
  { question: "Can you use too much compost?", answer: "Yes. More than 3 or 4 inches of fresh compost mixed into soil at once can create a nitrogen imbalance and a phosphorus buildup. Vegetables grow vegetative rather than fruiting, tomatoes get leggy, and over time, phosphorus runoff pollutes local waterways. For annual top-ups, 1 to 2 inches is plenty. For completely rebuilding a bed, you can use a higher rate once and then back off." },
  { question: "How deep should I top-dress a lawn with compost?", answer: "Apply 0.25 to 0.5 inches of finished compost as a top-dressing. Rake it in so most of it falls between blades of grass and touches the soil. For a 1,000 square foot lawn at a quarter inch, you need 20.8 cubic feet of compost, which is 0.77 cubic yards. Top-dress in early fall or early spring when the grass is actively growing and can take advantage of the nutrients." },
  { question: "How much does a cubic yard of compost weigh?", answer: "Finished compost weighs roughly 1,000 to 1,500 pounds per cubic yard depending on moisture content. That is roughly half the weight of topsoil. One cubic foot weighs about 45 pounds. A standard 1 cubic foot bag weighs 40 to 50 pounds and a 40 lb bag holds about 0.75 cubic feet." },
  { question: "Bulk vs bagged compost: which is better?", answer: "Bulk compost is dramatically cheaper, usually 30 to 50 dollars per cubic yard versus 5 to 8 dollars per 1 cubic foot bag (which works out to 135 to 215 dollars per cubic yard). Bulk is worth it above 1 to 2 cubic yards. The trade-off is quality: bagged compost from a reputable brand is almost always fully finished and weed-seed free, while bulk compost quality varies wildly by supplier — ask to see it before ordering." }
]) %>

